Note:
==============================================================================
Time Reference - Multiple Civil and Scientific Time Scales
==============================================================================

Time on Earth is not a single quantity. The civil clock most users see
(UTC) is one of several non-equivalent time scales, and mixing them is
the dominant source of bugs in satellite navigation, spaceflight,
high-frequency trading, and distributed databases that span continents.

This module enumerates the major scales and provides exact, leap-second-
aware conversions between them. Every DateTime carries an explicit
TimeReference; comparison across scales without an intermediate
conversion is an error contract violation.

The five scales tracked here:

  UTC  (Coordinated Universal Time)
       The civil reference broadcast by NTP servers. Tied to TAI but
       with leap seconds inserted (in 1972 and intermittently since) to
       keep |UT1 - UTC| < 0.9 s. Days are 86_400 seconds long EXCEPT on
       leap-second days, which contain 86_401 (positive leap) or
       86_399 (negative leap; never used to date) seconds.
       Standard: ITU-R TF.460-6, IERS Bulletin C.

  TAI  (International Atomic Time)
       The continuous atomic standard maintained by ~450 caesium clocks
       at BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures). Has no leap
       seconds; pure SI second since the 1958-01-01 epoch alignment
       with UT2. TAI = UTC + (leap seconds since 1972).
       Standard: BIPM Circular T, ITU-R TF.460-6.
       As of 2024: TAI - UTC = 37 s.

  GPS  (Global Positioning System time)
       Maintained by the United States Naval Observatory. Fixed offset
       from TAI: GPS = TAI - 19 s (the offset captures TAI's lead over
       UTC at the GPS epoch 1980-01-06 00:00:00 UTC, when TAI - UTC was
       19 s). GPS time has NO leap seconds.
       Standard: IS-GPS-200 §3.3.4 (Interface Specification).
       GPS week rollover handled outside this module's scope.

  GMT  (Greenwich Mean Time)
       Historically a mean solar time at the Greenwich meridian. Today
       used colloquially as a synonym for UTC; this module treats GMT
       and UTC as numerically identical (offset 0 between them) but
       preserves the label so output formatting and parsing can
       distinguish "Z" / "+00:00" (UTC) from "GMT" suffixes
       (RFC 5322 obsolete-zone form).
       Standard: ITU-R TF.460-6 (deprecates GMT as a scientific term).

  LocalCivil
       The wall-clock time observed at a given location, derived from
       UTC plus the offset from the IANA tz database for the relevant
       timezone. Subject to DST transitions and historical offset
       changes (e.g. Hawaii dropping DST in 1947). All LocalCivil
       comparisons across timezone boundaries MUST go through UTC.

  Monotonic
       The Instant-class reading exposed by instant.runa. Has no
       calendar interpretation. Comparisons with the calendar-based
       scales above are invalid.

References:
  ITU-R Recommendation TF.460-6 (Standard-frequency and time-signal
       emissions)
  IERS Bulletin C (leap-second announcements)
  IS-GPS-200 (GPS Interface Specification)
  Allan, Ashby, Hodge: "The Science of Timekeeping", HP Application
       Note 1289 (1997)
  Seago & Seidelmann: "The Mean-Solar-Time Origin of UTC and the
       Need for a New Atomic Standard", Astronomical Almanac
==============================================================================
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TimeReference enum (encoded as small Integer)
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TIME_REF_UTC as Integer is 0
Constant TIME_REF_TAI as Integer is 1
Constant TIME_REF_GPS as Integer is 2
Constant TIME_REF_GMT as Integer is 3
Constant TIME_REF_LOCAL_CIVIL as Integer is 4
Constant TIME_REF_MONOTONIC as Integer is 5

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Fixed offsets
Note: ============================================================================

Note: GPS = TAI - 19 s. From IS-GPS-200, §3.3.4: "GPS time is uniformly
Note: offset from TAI by an integer number of seconds, currently 19 s,
Note: equal to the number of leap seconds in UTC at GPS epoch
Note: (1980-01-06 00:00:00 UTC)."
Constant GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS as Integer is 19

Note: GPS epoch in Unix seconds: 1980-01-06 00:00:00 UTC
Note: = (10 leap years 1972-1979) * 366 + (4 normal years) * 365 + 6 days
Note: Confirmed: 315_964_800 (the canonical constant in every GPS receiver).
Constant GPS_EPOCH_UNIX_SECONDS as Integer is 315964800

Note: Unix epoch in TAI seconds (1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC).
Note: At 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC, TAI - UTC was 10 s (post-1972 epoch
Note: convention; pre-1972 a fractional rubber-second approximation
Note: applied). For modern Unix-to-TAI conversion we use 10 s as the
Note: baseline; current leap-second offset is added on top.
Constant UNIX_EPOCH_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS as Integer is 10

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Leap-second table (UTC seconds at which a leap second was inserted)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: This is the IERS leap-second table as of Bulletin C 67 (Jul 2023),
Note: confirming no leap second on 2024-01-01 and no leap second
Note: planned through Jun 2025. Each entry is the Unix timestamp at
Note: which TAI - UTC incremented by 1.
Note: Format: pairs (unix_seconds_at_insertion, tai_minus_utc_after).
Note: All historical insertions since the 1972 epoch alignment when
Note: TAI - UTC was set to 10 s exactly.
Note: SOURCE: https://hpiers.obspm.fr/iers/bul/bulc/Leap_Second.dat
Note: SOURCE: IERS Bulletin C as of July 2023 (no leap second 2024).

Constant LEAP_TABLE_ENTRIES as Integer is 28

Note: Encoded as flat Integer arrays (one for timestamps, one for offsets).
Note: We initialise via runtime functions to avoid relying on stage1's
Note: ability to populate static arrays. The actual table populator
Note: lives in time_reference_leap_init which the linker invokes
Note: lazily on first call to any conversion routine.

Let LEAP_TABLE_INITIALISED be 0
Let LEAP_TABLE_TIMESTAMPS be 0
Let LEAP_TABLE_OFFSETS be 0

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Process called "_leap_init_table" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Lazily populates the leap-second table on first access. The data
    is canonical IERS Bulletin C content current as of July 2023.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates two parallel int64 arrays of LEAP_TABLE_ENTRIES slots
    and writes the (unix_timestamp, tai_minus_utc) pairs. Uses
    Layout.allocate (tier-3 owned heap) since the table outlives any
    individual call. Idempotent: re-entry is a no-op once the
    INITIALISED flag is set.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Called at most once per process. Subsequent lookups skip this
    function entirely via the INITIALISED guard.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Allocates persistent memory; freed only on process exit.
    @End Security_Scope
    If LEAP_TABLE_INITIALISED is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let bytes_needed be LEAP_TABLE_ENTRIES multiplied by 8
    Let ts_buf be proc allocate from Layout with bytes_needed
    Let off_buf be proc allocate from Layout with bytes_needed
    If ts_buf is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If off_buf is equal to 0:
        Let dummy_free be proc deallocate from Layout with ts_buf
        Return -1
    End If
    Note: Each entry: unix timestamp of the SECOND immediately AFTER the
    Note: inserted leap second; the offset is TAI - UTC starting at that
    Note: instant. Pre-1972 alignment fixed TAI - UTC = 10 s.
    Let dummy0 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 0, 78796800
    Let dummy0o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 0, 11
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 8, 94694400
    Let dummy1o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 8, 12
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 16, 126230400
    Let dummy2o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 16, 13
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 24, 157766400
    Let dummy3o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 24, 14
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 32, 189302400
    Let dummy4o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 32, 15
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 40, 220924800
    Let dummy5o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 40, 16
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 48, 252460800
    Let dummy6o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 48, 17
    Let dummy7 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 56, 283996800
    Let dummy7o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 56, 18
    Let dummy8 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 64, 315532800
    Let dummy8o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 64, 19
    Let dummy9 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 72, 362793600
    Let dummy9o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 72, 20
    Let dummy10 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 80, 394329600
    Let dummy10o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 80, 21
    Let dummy11 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 88, 425865600
    Let dummy11o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 88, 22
    Let dummy12 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 96, 489024000
    Let dummy12o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 96, 23
    Let dummy13 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 104, 567993600
    Let dummy13o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 104, 24
    Let dummy14 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 112, 631152000
    Let dummy14o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 112, 25
    Let dummy15 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 120, 662688000
    Let dummy15o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 120, 26
    Let dummy16 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 128, 709948800
    Let dummy16o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 128, 27
    Let dummy17 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 136, 741484800
    Let dummy17o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 136, 28
    Let dummy18 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 144, 773020800
    Let dummy18o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 144, 29
    Let dummy19 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 152, 820454400
    Let dummy19o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 152, 30
    Let dummy20 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 160, 867715200
    Let dummy20o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 160, 31
    Let dummy21 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 168, 915148800
    Let dummy21o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 168, 32
    Let dummy22 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 176, 1136073600
    Let dummy22o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 176, 33
    Let dummy23 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 184, 1230768000
    Let dummy23o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 184, 34
    Let dummy24 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 192, 1341100800
    Let dummy24o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 192, 35
    Let dummy25 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 200, 1435708800
    Let dummy25o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 200, 36
    Let dummy26 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 208, 1483228800
    Let dummy26o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 208, 37
    Note: Entry 27 reserved for next IERS announcement (no leap second
    Note: as of Bulletin C 67). Initialised to sentinel max so the
    Note: lookup walks past it as "future, not applicable".
    Let dummy27 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with ts_buf, 216, 9223372036854775807
    Let dummy27o be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with off_buf, 216, 37
    Set LEAP_TABLE_TIMESTAMPS to ts_buf
    Set LEAP_TABLE_OFFSETS to off_buf
    Set LEAP_TABLE_INITIALISED to 1
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "leap_seconds_at_unix_time" takes unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns TAI - UTC at the given Unix timestamp, in seconds. For
    timestamps before the 1972 epoch the function returns 10 (the
    1972 baseline); for timestamps in the table it returns the
    largest stored offset whose insertion-time is <= unix_seconds.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Linear scan over the table from latest entry backward; for ~28
    entries this is faster than a binary-search dispatch and avoids
    the cmov chain on hot kernels. Lazily initialises the table.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(N) over ~28 entries. Suitable for inner loops at NTP-poll rates;
    use a cache wrapper for sub-microsecond rates.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read-only table lookup. No external input.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let init_rc be _leap_init_table()
    If init_rc is less than 0:
        Return UNIX_EPOCH_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
    End If
    If unix_seconds is less than 78796800:
        Return UNIX_EPOCH_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
    End If
    Let i be LEAP_TABLE_ENTRIES minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let offset_index be i multiplied by 8
        Let ts_at_i be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with LEAP_TABLE_TIMESTAMPS, offset_index
        If unix_seconds is greater than or equal to ts_at_i:
            Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with LEAP_TABLE_OFFSETS, offset_index
        End If
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While
    Return UNIX_EPOCH_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
End Process

Process called "tai_from_utc" takes utc_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a UTC Unix timestamp to TAI by adding TAI - UTC at that
    instant. The Unix timestamp must be the seconds elapsed since
    1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC, NOT NIST count and NOT GPS week.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns utc_unix_seconds + leap_seconds_at_unix_time(utc_unix_seconds).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One table lookup + one add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion. No syscalls.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let offset be leap_seconds_at_unix_time(utc_unix_seconds)
    Return utc_unix_seconds plus offset
End Process

Process called "utc_from_tai" takes tai_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of tai_from_utc. Because the leap-second function is keyed
    on Unix (UTC) time, we use a corrective iteration: start with the
    naive offset assuming no leap seconds, look up the offset at that
    candidate UTC time, subtract from TAI again, and repeat until the
    result is stable. Converges in at most two iterations in practice
    because leap-second insertions are discrete and well separated.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iterates up to four times then bails out with the best estimate.
    Each iteration: candidate_utc = tai - leap_seconds_at(candidate_utc).
    Termination is guaranteed because the offset increases monotonically
    and is bounded above by leap-second history.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case four lookups + four adds. Typical case two.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let candidate be tai_unix_seconds minus UNIX_EPOCH_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
    Let iter be 0
    While iter is less than 4:
        Let offset be leap_seconds_at_unix_time(candidate)
        Let new_candidate be tai_unix_seconds minus offset
        If new_candidate is equal to candidate:
            Return new_candidate
        End If
        Set candidate to new_candidate
        Set iter to iter plus 1
    End While
    Return candidate
End Process

Process called "gps_from_tai" takes tai_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    GPS time runs 19 seconds behind TAI by definition. The offset is
    fixed; no leap seconds apply.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Subtracts GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return tai_unix_seconds minus GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
End Process

Process called "tai_from_gps" takes gps_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of gps_from_tai.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Adds GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return gps_unix_seconds plus GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
End Process

Process called "gps_from_utc" takes utc_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convenience composition: GPS = TAI - 19 = UTC + (leap seconds - 19).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes TAI then subtracts GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One leap lookup + two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let tai be tai_from_utc(utc_unix_seconds)
    Return tai minus GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
End Process

Process called "utc_from_gps" takes gps_unix_seconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Convenience composition: UTC = TAI - leap = (GPS + 19) - leap.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes TAI from GPS, then UTC from TAI via the iterative inverse.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Cost of utc_from_tai plus one add.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure conversion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let tai be gps_unix_seconds plus GPS_TAI_OFFSET_SECONDS
    Return utc_from_tai(tai)
End Process

Process called "time_reference_name" takes ref as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning
    Maps a TimeReference enum value to its short label, suitable for
    diagnostic output and serialisation tags. Returns "?" on unknown
    values so the caller can detect corruption without crashing.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Switch on ref.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Trivial.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns static string constants.
    @End Security_Scope
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_UTC:
        Return "UTC"
    End If
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_TAI:
        Return "TAI"
    End If
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_GPS:
        Return "GPS"
    End If
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_GMT:
        Return "GMT"
    End If
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_LOCAL_CIVIL:
        Return "LocalCivil"
    End If
    If ref is equal to TIME_REF_MONOTONIC:
        Return "Monotonic"
    End If
    Return "?"
End Process

Process called "time_reference_is_comparable" takes a_ref as Integer, b_ref as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Two scales are comparable iff (1) they are identical, or (2) both
    are calendar-civil (UTC, GMT, TAI, GPS, LocalCivil) AND the caller
    has explicitly converted them to a common scale before comparison.
    Monotonic is comparable ONLY with itself. This predicate is the
    pre-condition for any cross-DateTime equality / ordering operator.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Equal scales are always comparable. Monotonic is never comparable
    with any other scale. All other pairs are comparable (with the
    understanding that the caller must perform the conversion before
    the comparison).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Constant time.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure predicate.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a_ref is equal to b_ref:
        Return 1
    End If
    If a_ref is equal to TIME_REF_MONOTONIC:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b_ref is equal to TIME_REF_MONOTONIC:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
